<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -403.464 3.2021" transformations="translations" pos="546.687 253.887" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="731.614" height="60.423" depth="33.055" valign="baseline" size="footnote">Try making this graph quickly with tikz\\
or moving things to the right place</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 172.913 -142.493" transformations="translations" pos="1065.43 257.089" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="520.735" height="100.617" depth="73.37" valign="baseline">\For{$i = 1 \ldots n$}
{
      $sum = sum + i^2$
}
\KwReturn{sum}</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 475.512 12.8088" transformations="translations" pos="546.687 253.887" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="515.472" height="60.445" depth="33.055" valign="baseline" size="footnote">Or adding pseudocode or equations in PowerPoint</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 8.00525 35.2231" transformations="translations" pos="444.22 68.1655" stroke="kn_peach" type="label" width="590.837" height="39.6" depth="11.715" valign="baseline">With IPE, both are easy!</text>
</page>
<page title="Other cool properties of IPE" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="149.05" depth="121.88" valign="top" style="itemize">\item IPE is super \ul{extensible} and \ul{configureable}:
\item New functionality can be added by writing Lua scripts
\item Style sheets allow defining colors, symbols, background templates and many more, and can be easily modified</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -15.21" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 467.07" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="110.511" depth="83.27" valign="top" style="itemize">\item IPE produces PDF documents and any PDF that was created by IPE can be opened in it and modified (like this tutorial)
\item You can steal other people&apos;s style sheets</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -30.4199" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 241.288" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="80.454" depth="53.13" valign="top" style="itemize">\item IPE is actually quite \ul{intuitive} and \ul{easy to use}
\item Many \ul{shortcuts} for fast editing</text>
</page>
<page title="Compilation" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="280.423" depth="253.55" valign="top" style="itemize">\item IPE needs to compile \LaTeX. There are two options:
\item You have the option to let IPE \ul{compile online} which requires no local  \LaTeX \ distribution. Internet connection is obviously required and your text will be forwarded to the compilation service.
\item If you have a \LaTeX \ distribution installed \ul{on your machine}, it can be used. This can be helpful if you want to use IPE in places where you don&apos;t have internet connection. You need to ensure that your installation has all packages used by the file you are editing.</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -14.3889" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 204.027" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="1680" height="86.4105" depth="59.125" valign="top" size="footnote">To switch between these option, go to the \emph{Help} tab and select \emph{Enable online Latex-compilation}. In the dialogue you can either enable or disable it, depending on what you are currently using.</text>
</page>
<page section="Basics of using IPE">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -352" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="kn_seeblau" type="minipage" width="1680" height="58.828" depth="31.405" valign="top" size="LARGE">Basics of using IPE</text>
</page>
<page title="Moving around" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="176.836" depth="149.71" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Using \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Ctrl+Zoom} (Mousewheel/Touchpad) is the most standard way to get your page where and how close you need it
\item The cursor is used as a reference point for zooming into/out of, so e.g. zooming in to the left of the page will make the page go to the right (you&apos;ll get it, it&apos;s similar to other drawing programs)</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -16" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 411.454" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="138.16" depth="110.99" valign="top" style="itemize">\item If you&apos;re lost, pressing \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{x} centers on the location of the cursor by panning
\item If you&apos;re totally lost, pressing  \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{\textbackslash} (backslash) fits the page to your view</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -112" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 229.485" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="1680" height="60.61" depth="33.22" valign="top" size="footnote">Try it! Zoom out with the cursor to the left of the page, then center on it by pressing x and then zoom in again.</text>
</page>
<page title="Selecting" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="110.781" depth="83.49" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Selecting in IPE can be a bit tricky, but first go to Selection mode by pressing  \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{S}
\item Objects are selected with the \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Left Mouse}</text>
<text pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 543.729" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="72.6495" depth="45.32" valign="top" style="item">Important: IPE only considers an \ul{object&apos;s border} for selecting which is why enabling the green boxes (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Ctrl+F12}) is helpful</text>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 384 32" stroke="kn_pinky" fill="kn_seeblau_20" pen="fat">
1024 384 m
1024 192 l
1360 192 l
1360 384 l
h
</path>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -528 30.915" transformations="translations" pos="464 336" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="1456" height="60.61" depth="33.22" valign="top" size="footnote">Try selecting this rectangle by clicking in the middle of it. Nothing happens.\\
Now try selecting by clicking on or close to the pink border. Works.</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 35.1718" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 157.511" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="105.298" depth="77.99" valign="top" style="item">Deselecting works by clicking somewhere where there is no object (e.g. off the page) or by selecting the same object again while holding down  \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Shift}</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 49.0214 30.4141" transformations="translations" pos="816 32" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="608" height="34.6225" depth="7.15" valign="top" size="footnote">(Now deselect the rectangle)</text>
</page>
<page title="Further selection tricks" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<layer name="beta"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<view layers="beta" active="beta"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="72.4625" depth="45.1" valign="top" style="item">As common in other programs, while holding down  \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Shift}, you can select multiple objects</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -321.935" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 620.438" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="72.6495" depth="45.32" valign="top" style="item">If multiple objects are close, selecting the right one may require  \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{holding down the left mouse} and tabbing through them with  \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Space}</text>
<text layer="beta" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 331.25" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 438.75" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="209.292" depth="182.325" valign="top" style="itemize">\item You can also select (multiple) objects by making a box through holding down the left mouse button and moving it
\item If you go from left to right, it selects all objects \ul{entirely contained} in the box
\item But if you go from right to left, it selects all objects that \ul{intersect} the box</text>
<path layer="alpha" matrix="1 0 0 1 258.5 39.6472" stroke="black" fill="kn_peach">
61.8497 0 0 61.8497 504.864 551.097 e
</path>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 183.963 -82.4662" stroke="black" fill="kn_petrol">
