<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -258.793 98.8784" transformations="translations" pos="288.418 194.043" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="507.82" height="112.112" depth="84.865" valign="top" size="footnote">Try selecting only the blue-green-ish rectangles on the left using these techniques</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 897.23 125.529" transformations="translations" pos="288.418 194.043" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="465.095" height="138.738" depth="111.54" valign="top" size="footnote">Or only the dark blue plus both red-ish ones (forming the diagonal from top left to bottom right)</text>
</page>
<page title="Drawing shapes" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<layer name="beta"/>
<layer name="gamma"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha beta" active="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha beta gamma" active="gamma"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="286.099" depth="259.27" valign="top" style="itemize">\item You can draw a bunch of different shapes using the tools in the top bar
\item Shapes are each defined by a characteristic set of \ul{control points} which are placed with the \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Left Mouse}
\item \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Shift} may act as a modifier (e.g. for making squares with the rectangle tool)
\item The control points of  lines can be undone by pressing \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Del} and lines are finished using a \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{double-click}</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 156.252 67.1396" transformations="translations" pos="506.928 104.931" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="599.374" height="34.419" depth="6.985" valign="top" size="footnote">Draw your favorite shape here:</text>
<text layer="beta" matrix="1 0 0 1 194.094 1.22069" transformations="translations" pos="506.928 104.931" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="518.806" height="60.423" depth="33.055" valign="top" size="footnote" style="center">Now delete it, by selecting it and pressing \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Del}!!</text>
<text layer="gamma" matrix="1 0 0 1 -1191.42 10.4703" transformations="translations" pos="1180.77 37.7911" stroke="kn_grau" type="label" width="638.544" height="32.032" depth="16.555" valign="baseline" size="footnote">(This is how you \ul{delete} anything)</text>
<path stroke="kn_grau" arrow="normal/small">
643.648 60.9848 m
679.049 34.1289
730.319 39.0118 c
</path>
<path layer="alpha" stroke="kn_grau" pen="thin">
1278.42 275.832 m
1278.42 23.1424 l
1676.38 23.1424 l
1676.38 275.832 l
h
</path>
</page>
<page title="Object properties" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -0.00028352" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="176.429" depth="149.325" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Your new object gets the \ul{properties} that are currently displayed on the left
\item To change your object, either select it and then change the properties on the left or go to the context menu with \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Right Mouse} and change it there</text>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 124.514 -7.32432" stroke="black" fill="kn_seeblau_35">
705.905 143.994 m
824.315 320.998 l
932.959 146.435 l
1050.15 259.962 l
1109.96 202.588 l
1310.16 405.228 l
</path>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 41.5045 -47.6081" transformations="translations" pos="118.738 383.255" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="582.284" height="108.235" depth="80.96" valign="top" size="footnote">Change this object&apos;s properties to make it a fat green line (no fill) with a large forward arrow</text>
</page>
<page title="Translate, rotate, stretch" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="116.215" depth="88.99" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Move objects around by going to Translating mode by pressing \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{T}
\item Rotate objects in Rotating mode: \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{R}
\item Make objects bigger/smaller/stretch them in Stretching mode: \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{E}</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 275.883" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 250.562" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="181.913" depth="154.825" valign="top" style="itemize">\item \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Shift} acts as a modifier: 
\item When translating, it allows moving either horizontally or vertically, but not both
\item When stretching, it actually scales the object, keeping its proportions</text>
<path matrix="0.325748 0 0 0.325748 115.533 81.8212" stroke="black" fill="kn_pinky_20">
141.932 156.201 m
141.932 35.3497 l
262.783 35.3497 l
262.783 156.201 l
h
</path>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -107.423 56.045" transformations="translations" pos="1389.51 133.007" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="367.438" height="81.8895" depth="54.615" valign="top" size="footnote">Make the pink square over there cover this blue one</text>
<path matrix="-0.695678 0.718354 -0.718354 -0.695678 2045.95 -682.822" stroke="kn_grau" fill="kn_seeblau_35">
1130.72 148.877 m
1130.72 14.5974 l
1265 14.5974 l
1265 148.877 l
h
</path>
</page>
<page title="Snapping" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<layer name="beta"/>
<layer name="gamma"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<view layers="beta" active="beta"/>
<view layers="gamma" active="gamma"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="99.836" depth="72.6" valign="top" style="item">IPE offers a couple of snapping modes that are very useful for making nice-looking figures. They can be toggled at the very top left or via shortcuts</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -18.3108" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 565.564" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="105.27" depth="77.99" valign="top" style="item">Use \ul{grid snapping} (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{F7}) to aid making regular alignments
\item You can change the grid size in the middle of the top toolbar (where it says &apos;xy&apos; pts)</text>
<path stroke="black" pen="thin" cap="1">
1280.86 511.431 m
1280.86 511.431 l
</path>
<path stroke="black" fill="kn_petrol" pen="thin">
1008 224 m
1008 112 l
1120 112 l
1120 224 l
h
</path>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -72.0225 42.7937" transformations="translations" pos="140 224" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="887.366" height="112.579" depth="85.36" valign="top" size="footnote">Use grid snapping to make a new square of equal size to the green one, spaced exactly one such square size apart to the right (you may have to change grid size)</text>
<text layer="beta" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="214.967" depth="187.935" valign="top" style="itemize">\item \ul{Vertex snapping} (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{F4}) allows snapping to end points or corners of shapes
\item \ul{Control point snapping} (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Shift + F4}) allows snapping to the points that were used to make a shape
\item \ul{Boundary snapping} (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{F5}) allows snapping to continuous boundarys (edges) of objects or the page&apos;s frame</text>
<text layer="gamma" matrix="1 0 0 1 91.4912 452.118" transformations="translations" pos="91.3198 219.505" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="1314.38" height="229.141" depth="202.18" valign="top" size="script" style="enumerate">\item Select your favorite color in the top color property field (stroke color)
\item Trace parts of the arc of the circle at the bottom with a circular arc (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{A}). Select the circle center first (control point snapping), then two points on the boundary (boundary snapping)
\item Now create a line (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{P}) that goes from one end of the arc you just created (vertex snapping) to the circle&apos;s center and then to the arc&apos;s other end
\item Select both, the arc and the wedge shaped line, right click and then select \emph{Join paths}
\item Give your new shape a fill (if it doesn&apos;t have one already) and your result should look something like the one on the left (label optional)</text>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 -287.09 22.8409" stroke="black" pen="thin">
81.8884 0 0 81.8884 1127.09 103.878 e
</path>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 798.432" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 -28.5998" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="39.842" depth="12.375" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Let&apos;s use these snapping modes to make a cool figure!</text>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 -287.09 22.8409" stroke="black" pen="thin">
81.8884 0 0 81.8884 1127.09 103.878 e
</path>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 -1061.37 352.085" stroke="black" pen="thin">
81.8884 0 0 81.8884 1127.09 103.878 e
</path>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 -1427.79 295.273" stroke="kn_peach_d" fill="kn_peach_20">
1575.36 163.34 m
81.8884 0 0 81.8884 1493.51 160.689 1497.3 242.49 a
1493.51 160.689 l
h
</path>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -16.1696 -8.87781" transformations="translations" pos="100.487 485.504" stroke="kn_peach_d" type="label" width="35.255" height="23.5895" depth="0" valign="baseline" style="math">\alpha</text>
</page>
<page title="Text objects" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<layer name="beta"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<view layers="beta" active="beta"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="39.9795" depth="12.595" valign="top" style="item">There are multiple ways to add text to your figures/presentations:</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -6.34356" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 685.426" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="138.16" depth="110.99" valign="top" style="itemize">\item A \ul{text label} (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{L}) is the simplest, creating a text object that fits to its content&apos;s width (typically one line)
\item For multiple lines in a label, change its \emph{Type} to `minipage&apos; in the context menu and use manual line breaks</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -126.085" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 508.958" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="110.973" depth="83.71" valign="top" style="itemize">\item For a \ul{paragraph} (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{L}), you can manually define its width and text will be broken into lines automatically according to the width
\item Changing the width is possible through the context menu</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -11.1012" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 152.231" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="72.6495" depth="45.32" valign="top" style="item">Mainly for presentations, a \ul{text box} (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{F10}) inserts a text object that spans the entire page frame below the lowest text on the page</text>
<text layer="beta" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="116.215" depth="88.99" valign="top" style="itemize">\item All text objects have two options:
\item The \emph{Style} defines the environment, e.g. math, itemize etc.
\item The \emph{Size}...well, you can guess</text>
<text matrix="0.969199 0.246278 -0.246278 0.969199 76.247 -112.22" transformations="rigid" pos="172.773 450.18" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="628.012" height="60.61" depth="33.22" valign="top" size="footnote">Feel free to try creating labels, paragraphs or text boxes here</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 15.8589 12.6871" transformations="translations" pos="994.263 499.343" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="607.395" height="97.658" depth="70.4" valign="top" size="script">If you want to rotate a label or paragraph, you need to change its \emph{Transformation} to `rigid&apos; first through the context menu</text>
<path stroke="kn_grau" arrow="normal/normal">
975.233 440.665 m
848.361 332.825
627.923 364.542 c
</path>
</page>
<page title="Aligning" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="149.435" depth="122.32" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Options for \ul{aligning and distributing} objects can be found under \emph{Ipelets $&gt;$ Align \&amp; distribute}
\item Objects are moved to align with the reference object
\item Logical shortcuts for aligning use the modifier \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Shift} and:</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -16 -66.6667" transformations="translations" pos="128 528" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1408" height="217.789" depth="190.85" valign="top" size="small">\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{T} for aligning at the top\\
\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{B} for aligning at the bottom\\
\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{L} for aligning on the left side\\
\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{R} for aligning on the right side\\
\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{C} for aligning the center points\\
\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{V} for aligning vertical center points\\
\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{H} for aligning horizontal center points\\</text>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 10.2778 -90.4444" stroke="black" fill="kn_seeblau_35">
1138.06 368.889 m
1138.06 262 l
1257.28 262 l
1257.28 368.889 l
h
</path>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 4.11111 -28.7778" stroke="black" fill="kn_pinky_35">
1337.44 268.167 m
1337.44 134.556 l
1483.39 134.556 l
1483.39 268.167 l
h
</path>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 2.05556 361.778" transformations="translations" pos="1125.72 70.8333" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="472.778" height="60.214" depth="32.89" valign="top" size="footnote">Here are two objects \\to try it out on:</text>
</page>
<page title="Distributing and other alignment tricks" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="72.6495" depth="45.32" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Distributing multiple objects is possible from the same menu as aligning (no predefined shortcuts)</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -10.2778" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 620.03" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="176.044" depth="148.94" valign="top" style="itemize">\item The option to \emph{distribute top to bottom} can be interesting to match one object&apos;s top to another objects bottom, i.e. putting them right above another
\item If you \emph{set skip} (a value in pts) first, that amount of space will be left between the objects</text>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 431.667 6.16667" stroke="black" fill="kn_pinky_35">
167.833 235.278 m
167.833 200.333 l
1181.22 200.333 l
1181.22 235.278 l
h
</path>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 285.723 -121.278" stroke="black" fill="kn_seeblau_35">
167.833 235.278 m
167.833 200.333 l
1181.22 200.333 l
1181.22 235.278 l
h
</path>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -1235.39 10.2778" transformations="translations" pos="1257.28 233.222" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="411.111" height="112.239" depth="84.975" valign="top" size="footnote">Make these two bars align horizontally and space them 10 pts apart vertically</text>
</page>
<page title="Drawing graphs" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="72.6495" depth="45.32" valign="top" style="itemize">\item As computer scientists (especially algorithmics enthusiasts), we need to draw graphs from time to time. IPE makes this easy!
</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -7.92945" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 620.03" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="143.974" depth="116.82" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Use marks (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{M}) as nodes/vertices. Mark shapes are configurable through the properties (third from the bottom), but `disk&apos; works well
\item Enable vertex snapping mode and draw each edge as a separate line (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{P}) between two vertices (should show a red guide element)</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -79.2945" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 377.131" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="72.6495" depth="45.32" valign="top" style="itemize">\item If you do this, you can now move your graph nodes with the corresponding tool, and all connected edges will follow!</text>
<image matrix="2.84223 0 0 2.84223 1569.94 198.776" rect="0 0 28 28" bitmap="3"/>
<use matrix="1 0 0 1 -218.391 -10.3015" name="mark/disk(sx)" pos="364.665 148.862" size="normal" stroke="black"/>
<use matrix="1 0 0 1 -218.391 -10.3015" name="mark/disk(sx)" pos="347.22 41.0211" size="normal" stroke="black"/>
