</group>
<path matrix="1 0 0 1 29.2299 65.7673" stroke="kn_seeblau">
948.145 408.48 m
1223.39 325.662 l
</path>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 28.2019 -115.122" transformations="translations" pos="482.333 453.167" stroke="kn_seegruen" type="label" width="15.235" height="39.589" depth="0" valign="baseline">I</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 9.70191 -117.177" transformations="translations" pos="597.444 455.222" stroke="kn_bordeaux" type="label" width="30.4645" height="39.589" depth="0" valign="baseline">II</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 536.499 -115.122" transformations="translations" pos="887.278 453.167" stroke="kn_peach" type="label" width="45.6995" height="39.589" depth="0" valign="baseline">III</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 589.944 -115.122" transformations="translations" pos="482.333 453.167" stroke="kn_pinky" type="label" width="15.235" height="39.589" depth="0" valign="baseline">I</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 642.968 -117.177" transformations="translations" pos="597.444 455.222" stroke="kn_seeblau" type="label" width="30.4645" height="39.589" depth="0" valign="baseline">II</text>
<text layer="gamma" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 38.9732" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 239.827" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="146.344" depth="119.185" valign="top" style="itemize">\item This final presentation will consist of 5 slides -- one for each view.
\item The first slide will show layer alpha of page 1. The second slide will additionally show the layer beta of page 1 and keeps alpha visible. This is typical for \ul{incrementally revealing} e.g. bullet points.</text>
<text layer="delta" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -26.7941" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 305.594" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="105.518" depth="78.21" valign="top" style="item">Notice how the last slide (view III of page 2) adds two new layers (gamma and delta) compared the view before and also drops the first layer? Everything is possible!</text>
<text layer="epsilon" matrix="1 0 0 1 -6.21465 200.945" transformations="translations" pos="55.8851 72.2556" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="1580.66" height="138.562" depth="111.43" valign="top" size="footnote">Take a look at the layers and views of this page (shown on the left)!\\
Play with which layers are active in which view to get a better understanding.\\
If you enable all layers, you&apos;ll see that this IPE page is actually massively overloaded.
This is not good practice (better to create a new page than overloading views and layers), but sometimes helpful.</text>
</page>
<page title="Shortcuts" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="78.3035" depth="50.985" valign="top" style="itemize">\item New pages can be created with \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Ctrl+I}
\item Cuting/Copying/Pasting pages can be done with \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Ctrl+Shift+X/C/V}</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -28.3333" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 608.712" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="39.787" depth="12.32" valign="top" style="item">A new layer can be created with \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Ctrl+Shift+N}</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -54.6111" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 508.605" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="100.028" depth="72.765" valign="top" style="item">Most commonly, you will probably need the shortcut \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Ctrl+Shift+I} to create a new view and new layer that gets activated for the new view</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -133.444" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 287.811" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="67.111" depth="39.765" valign="top" size="small" style="item">Deleting is not possible via shortcuts. Pages and views can be deleted from the corresponding tabs at the top, layers from the list on the left</text>
<text transformations="translations" pos="313.778 301.056" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="1210.72" height="55.902" depth="28.545" valign="top" size="footnote">Try adding a new view and layer, add something to it and go back and forth to see the effect</text>
</page>
<page title="Presentation style sheets" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="280.643" depth="253.77" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Presentations require certain properties (landscape format, bigger font sizes etc.) that need a \ul{dedicated style sheet}
\item IPE&apos;s installation supplies a `presentation&apos; style sheet for 4:3 format slides in the subfolder `styles&apos;. Add this and remove the style sheet `basic&apos; from a new IPE project to get started with a presentation.
\item Presentation style sheets can also define a design template for the pages</text>
</page>
<page title="Using this template" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<layer name="beta"/>
<layer name="gamma"/>
<layer name="delta"/>
<layer name="epsilon"/>
<layer name="zeta"/>
<view layers="alpha beta" active="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha gamma" active="gamma"/>
<view layers="alpha zeta" active="zeta"/>
<view layers="alpha delta" active="delta"/>
<view layers="alpha epsilon" active="epsilon"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="143.401" depth="116.27" valign="top" style="itemize">\item This template (contained in the `algoKN&apos; style file) gives you the look you see in this presentation (and for example all corporate design colors of the University of Konstanz)
\item Here are some pointers on how to use it:</text>
<text layer="beta" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -20.5556" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 478.329" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="176.825" depth="149.71" valign="top" style="itemize">\item To add a \ul{page title}, press \textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Ctrl+P}. Here you can also create bookmarks for your PDF with the sections (pretty cool, right?)
\item The \ul{bottom bar} requires you to define the following commands in the Latex preamble of the document properties (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Ctrl+Shift+P}):
\begin{verbatim} \bottomleft \bottommiddle \bottomright \end{verbatim}</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -26.7222 0" transformations="translations" pos="79.4444 89.3333" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="1574.56" height="34.6225" depth="7.15" valign="top" size="footnote" style="center">Try to change the bottom bar and the title of this page now!</text>
<text layer="gamma" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 478.329" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="241.851" depth="214.94" valign="top" style="itemize">\item The \ul{title page} can be inserted by using a \emph{symbol} via the tab \emph{Ipelets $&gt;$ Symbols $&gt;$ use symbol} and selecting `titlePage&apos; from the second drop down. Use vertex snapping to fit it on a page. 
\item It requires you to define the following commands in the Latex preamble of the document properties (\textcolor{kn_seegruen}{Ctrl+Shift+P}):
\begin{verbatim}\fulltitle \subtitle \name \subject \displayDate \end{verbatim}
They may be left empty, but need to be defined.</text>
<text layer="delta" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -47.2778" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 478.329" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="143.594" depth="116.38" valign="top" style="itemize">\item If you want to use this template, you are probably best off using the .ipe file that has this configured already
\item Alternatively, you can copy the preamble from this document or from the Git repository</text>
<text layer="epsilon" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -104.833" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 478.329" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="105.133" depth="77.825" valign="top" style="item">Pro tip: If you do not want the template background (logo, bottom bar) on a given page, add a layer named `BACKGROUND&apos; (all caps!) to it!</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 9.25 -11.5092" transformations="translations" pos="260.333 169.5" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="1140.83" height="34.441" depth="6.985" valign="top" size="footnote">Try it now and see how the logo and bottom bar disappear!</text>
<text layer="zeta" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -14.3889" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 478.329" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="176.644" depth="149.545" valign="top" style="itemize">\item \ul{Page numbers} can be (de)activated in the document properties and their appearance is determined by the style sheet
\item \begin{verbatim}\ul{...}, \subheader{...}, \define{...}\end{verbatim} are (pre)defined \ul{commands} set up to help you create a consistent appearance throughout this template</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -6.1665 22.6111" transformations="translations" pos="81.5 97.5556" stroke="kn_grau" type="minipage" width="1529.33" height="34.6225" depth="7.15" valign="top" size="footnote">Try adding a label or text box here and use the define or subheader command:</text>
</page>
<page title="Presentation tips" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -65.7778" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="253.237" depth="226.38" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Text boxes are great for presentations
\item Remember the shortcuts for new pages, new views, and new layers -- you&apos;ll be needing them
\item Transfer good coding practices to making presentations and make use of pages and layers
\item The subheader command or subheadline text style are great for separating topics on a page:</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -197.333" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 400.85" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="39.655" depth="12.21" valign="top" style="subheadline">Presenting your slides</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 603.583" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 166.929" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="39.655" depth="12.21" valign="top" style="subheadline">Making your slides</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 0 32.8889" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 109.374" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="80.454" depth="53.13" valign="top" style="itemize">\item Your slides can be presented with any PDF viewer
\item IPE comes with the \ul{IPE presenter} application which works great</text>
<text matrix="1 0 0 1 -166.5 -423.444" transformations="translations" pos="1532.15 711.8" stroke="kn_signal_red" type="minipage" width="489.222" height="123.673" depth="96.47" valign="top" size="footnote" style="itemize">\item Stay in the frame (grid pattern box)!
\item Don&apos;t overload a page visually</text>
</page>
<page section="Conclusion">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" matrix="1 0 0 1 0 -352" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="kn_seeblau" type="minipage" width="1680" height="49.346" depth="22" valign="top" size="LARGE">Conclusion</text>
</page>
<page title="Further resources" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="247.775" depth="220.88" valign="top" style="itemize">\item The \ul{official IPE Manual}:\\
https://otfried.github.io/ipe/index.html\\
(or via \emph{Help $&gt;$ ipe manual} from inside IPE)
\item For making your \ul{own presentation template}:\\
https://olejorik.github.io/post/ipe\_presentation\_template/
% Copy this link, not the one above: https://olejorik.github.io/post/ipe_presentation_template/
\item The Github link for this presentation and its \ul{README}:\\
missing</text>
</page>
<page title="Final remark" subsection="">
<layer name="alpha"/>
<view layers="alpha" active="alpha"/>
<text layer="alpha" pin="h" transformations="translations" pos="0 770" stroke="black" type="minipage" width="1680" height="214.588" depth="187.55" valign="top" style="itemize">\item IPE is really easy to get a hang of and we hoped this tutorial helped you get a good feel for it!
\item We encourage you to take a look at the style file used in this presentation, modify it, or make your own!
\item Create your next presentation and your figures with IPE to impress Prof. Storandt!</text>
